# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vector-network-analyzer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Directional couplers are most frequently constructed from two coupled transmission lines set close enough together such that energy passing through one is coupled to the other.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This technique is favoured at the microwave frequencies where transmission line designs are commonly used to implement many circuit elements.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] However, lumped component devices are also possible at lower frequencies, such as the audio frequencies encountered in telephony.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Also at microwave frequencies, particularly the higher bands, waveguide designs can be used.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Many of these waveguide couplers correspond to one of the conducting transmission line designs, but there are also types that are unique to waveguide.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Directional couplers and power dividers have many applications.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] These include providing a signal sample for measurement or monitoring, feedback, combining feeds to and from antennas, antenna beam forming, providing taps for cable distributed systems such as cable TV, and separating transmitted and received signals on telephone lines.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The symbols most often used for directional couplers are shown in figure 1.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The symbol may have the coupling factor in dB marked on it.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Port 1 is the input port where power is applied.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Port 3 is the coupled port where a portion of the power applied to port 1 appears.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Port 2 is the transmitted port where the power from port 1 is outputted, less the portion that went to port 3.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Directional couplers are frequently symmetrical so there also exists port 4, the isolated port.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A portion of the power applied to port 2 will be coupled to port 4.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] However, the device is not normally used in this mode and port 4 is usually terminated with a matched load (typically 50 ohms).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This termination can be internal to the device and port 4 is not accessible to the user.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Effectively, this results in a 3-port device, hence the utility of the second symbol for directional couplers in figure 1.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] in this article have the meaning "parameter *P* at port *a* due to an input at port *b*".
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A symbol for power dividers is shown in figure 2.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Power dividers and directional couplers are in all essentials the same class of device.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] *Directional coupler* tends to be used for 4-port devices that are only loosely coupled – that is, only a small fraction of the input power appears at the coupled port.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] *Power divider* is used for devices with tight coupling (commonly, a power divider will provide half the input power at each of its output ports – a 3 dB divider) and is usually considered a 3-port device.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Common properties desired for all directional couplers are wide operational bandwidth, high directivity, and a good impedance match at all ports when the other ports are terminated in matched loads.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Some of these, and other, general characteristics are discussed below.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] where P1 is the input power at port 1 and P3 is the output power from the coupled port (see figure 1).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The coupling factor represents the primary property of a directional coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Coupling factor is a negative quantity, it cannot exceed 0 dB for a passive device, and in practice does not exceed −3 dB since more than this would result in more power output from the coupled port than power from the transmitted port – in effect their roles would be reversed.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Although a negative quantity, the minus sign is frequently dropped (but still implied) in running text and diagrams and a few authors go so far as to define it as a *positive* quantity.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Coupling is not constant, but varies with frequency.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] While different designs may reduce the variance, a perfectly flat coupler theoretically cannot be built.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Directional couplers are specified in terms of the coupling accuracy at the frequency band center.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The insertion loss of an ideal directional coupler will consist entirely of the coupling loss.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In a real directional coupler, however, the insertion loss consists of a combination of coupling loss, dielectric loss, conductor loss, and VSWR loss.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Depending on the frequency range, coupling loss becomes less significant above 15 dB coupling where the other losses constitute the majority of the total loss.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The theoretical insertion loss (dB) vs coupling (dB) for a dissipationless coupler is shown in the graph of figure 3 and the table below.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Isolation can also be defined between the two output ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In this case, one of the output ports is used as the input; the other is considered the output port while the other two ports (input and isolated) are terminated by matched loads.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The isolation between the input and the isolated ports may be different from the isolation between the two output ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] For example, the isolation between ports 1 and 4 can be 30 dB while the isolation between ports 2 and 3 can be a different value such as 25 dB.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Isolation can be estimated from the coupling plus return loss.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The isolation should be as high as possible.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In actual couplers the isolated port is never completely isolated.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Waveguide directional couplers will have the best isolation.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Directivity is directly related to isolation.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] where: P3 is the output power from the coupled port and P4 is the power output from the isolated port.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The directivity should be as high as possible.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The directivity is very high at the design frequency and is a more sensitive function of frequency because it depends on the cancellation of two wave components.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Waveguide directional couplers will have the best directivity.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In general, $\tau \$ and $\kappa \$ are complex, frequency dependent, numbers.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The zeroes on the matrix main diagonal are a consequence of perfect matching – power input to any port is not reflected back to that same port.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The zeroes on the matrix antidiagonal are a consequence of perfect isolation between the input and isolated port.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] since the power entering the input port must all leave by one of the other two ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Non-zero main diagonal entries are related to return loss, and non-zero antidiagonal entries are related to isolation by similar expressions.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Some authors define the port numbers with ports 3 and 4 interchanged.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This results in a scattering matrix that is no longer all-zeroes on the antidiagonal.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This terminology defines the power difference in dB between the two output ports of a 3 dB hybrid.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In an ideal hybrid circuit, the difference should be 0 dB.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] However, in a practical device the amplitude balance is frequency dependent and departs from the ideal 0 dB difference.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The phase difference between the two output ports of a hybrid coupler should be 0°, 90°, or 180° depending on the type used.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] However, like amplitude balance, the phase difference is sensitive to the input frequency and typically will vary a few degrees.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The most common form of directional coupler is a pair of coupled transmission lines.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] They can be realised in a number of technologies including coaxial and the planar technologies (stripline and microstrip).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] An implementation in stripline is shown in figure 4 of a quarter-wavelength (λ/4) directional coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The power on the coupled line flows in the opposite direction to the power on the main line, hence the port arrangement is not the same as shown in figure 1, but the numbering remains the same.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] For this reason it is sometimes called a *backward coupler*.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The *main line* is the section between ports 1 and 2 and the *coupled line* is the section between ports 3 and 4.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Since the directional coupler is a linear device, the notations on figure 1 are arbitrary.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Any port can be the input, (an example is seen in figure 20) which will result in the directly connected port being the transmitted port, the adjacent port being the coupled port, and the diagonal port being the isolated port.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] On some directional couplers, the main line is designed for high power operation (large connectors), while the coupled port may use a small connector, such as an SMA connector.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The internal load power rating may also limit operation on the coupled line.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Accuracy of coupling factor depends on the dimensional tolerances for the spacing of the two coupled lines.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] For planar printed technologies this comes down to the resolution of the printing process which determines the minimum track width that can be produced and also puts a limit on how close the lines can be placed to each other.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This becomes a problem when very tight coupling is required and 3 dB couplers often use a different design.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] However, tightly coupled lines can be produced in air stripline which also permits manufacture by printed planar technology.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In this design the two lines are printed on *opposite* sides of the dielectric rather than side by side.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The coupling of the two lines across their width is much greater than the coupling when they are edge-on to each other.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The λ/4 coupled-line design is good for coaxial and stripline implementations but does not work so well in the now popular microstrip format, although designs do exist.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The reason for this is that microstrip is not a homogeneous medium – there are two different mediums above and below the transmission strip.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This leads to transmission modes other than the usual TEM mode found in conductive circuits.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The propagation velocities of even and odd modes are different leading to signal dispersion.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A better solution for microstrip is a coupled line much shorter than λ/4, shown in figure 5, but this has the disadvantage of a coupling factor which rises noticeably with frequency.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A variation of this design sometimes encountered has the coupled line a higher impedance than the main line such as shown in figure 6.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This design is advantageous where the coupler is being fed to a detector for power monitoring.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The higher impedance line results in a higher RF voltage for a given main line power making the work of the detector diode easier.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The frequency range specified by manufacturers is that of the coupled line.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The main line response is much wider: for instance a coupler specified as 2–4 GHz might have a main line which could operate at 1–5 GHz.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The coupled response is periodic with frequency.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] For example, a λ/4 coupled-line coupler will have responses at *n*λ/4 where *n* is an odd integer.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This preferred response gets obvious when a short impulse on the main line is followed through the coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] When the impulse on the main line reaches the coupled line a signal of the same polarity is induced on the coupled line similar to the response of an RC-high-pass.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This leads to two non-inverted pulses on the coupled line that travel in opposite direction to each other.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] When the pulse on the main line leaves the coupled line an inverted signal is induced on the coupled line, triggering two inverted impulses that travel in opposite direction to each other.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Both impulses on the coupled line that go in the same direction as the pulse on the main line are of opposite polarity.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] They cancel each other so there is no response on the exit of the coupled line in forward direction.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The pulses on the coupled line that travel in the opposite direction to the pulse on the main line are also of opposite polarity to each other but the second impulse is delayed by twice the delay of the parallel line.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] For a λ/4 coupled-line the total delay length is λ/2 so the second signal is inverted and this gives a maximum response on the coupled port.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A single λ/4 coupled section is good for bandwidths of less than an octave.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] To achieve greater bandwidths multiple λ/4 coupling sections are used.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The design of such couplers proceeds in much the same way as the design of distributed-element filters.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Ripple is the maximum variation in output of the coupled port in its passband, usually quoted as plus or minus a value in dB from the nominal coupling factor.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] It can be shown that coupled-line directional couplers have $\tau \$ purely real and $\kappa \$ purely imaginary at all frequencies.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This leads to a simplification of the S-matrix and the result that the coupled port is always in quadrature phase (90°) with the output port.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Some applications make use of this phase difference.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The branch-line coupler consists of two parallel transmission lines physically coupled together with two or more branch lines between them.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The branch lines are spaced λ/4 apart and represent sections of a multi-section filter design in the same way as the multiple sections of a coupled-line coupler except that here the coupling of each section is controlled with the impedance of the branch lines.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The main and coupled line are $\scriptstyle {\sqrt {2}}$ of the system impedance.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The more sections there are in the coupler, the higher is the ratio of impedances of the branch lines.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] High impedance lines have narrow tracks and this usually limits the design to three sections in planar formats due to manufacturing limitations.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A similar limitation applies for coupling factors looser than 10 dB; low coupling also requires narrow tracks.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Coupled lines are a better choice when loose coupling is required, but branch-line couplers are good for tight coupling and can be used for 3 dB hybrids.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Branch-line couplers usually do not have such a wide bandwidth as coupled lines.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This style of coupler is good for implementing in high-power, air dielectric, solid bar formats as the rigid structure is easy to mechanically support.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Branch line couplers can be used as crossovers as an alternative to air bridges, which in some applications cause an unacceptable amount of coupling between the lines being crossed.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] An ideal branch-line crossover theoretically has no coupling between the two paths through it.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The design is a 3-branch coupler equivalent to two 3 dB 90° hybrid couplers connected in cascade.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The result is effectively a 0 dB coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] It will cross over the inputs to the diagonally opposite outputs with a phase delay of 90° in both lines.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The construction of the Lange coupler is similar to the interdigital filter with paralleled lines interleaved to achieve the coupling.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] It is used for strong couplings in the range 3 dB to 6 dB.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The earliest transmission line power dividers were simple T-junctions.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] These suffer from very poor isolation between the output ports – a large part of the power reflected back from port 2 finds its way into port 3.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] It can be shown that it is not theoretically possible to simultaneously match all three ports of a passive, lossless three-port and poor isolation is unavoidable.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The term *hybrid coupler* originally applied to 3 dB coupled-line directional couplers, that is, directional couplers in which the two outputs are each half the input power.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This synonymously meant a quadrature 3 dB coupler with outputs 90° out of phase.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Now any matched 4-port with isolated arms and equal power division is called a hybrid or hybrid coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Other types can have different phase relationships.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In this article *hybrid coupler* without qualification means a coupled-line hybrid.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The Wilkinson power divider consists of two parallel *uncoupled* λ/4 transmission lines.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The input is fed to both lines in parallel and the outputs are terminated with twice the system impedance bridged between them.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The Wilkinson power divider solves the matching problem of the simple T-junction: it has low VSWR at all ports and high isolation between output ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The input and output impedances at each port are designed to be equal to the characteristic impedance of the microwave system.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Coupled-line directional couplers are described above.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] When the coupling is designed to be 3 dB it is called a hybrid coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The two output ports have a 90° phase difference (-*i* to −1) and so this is a 90° hybrid.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The hybrid ring coupler, also called the rat-race coupler, is a four-port 3 dB directional coupler consisting of a 3λ/2 ring of transmission line with four lines at the intervals shown in figure 12.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Power input at port 1 splits and travels both ways round the ring.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] At ports 2 and 3 the signal arrives in phase and adds whereas at port 4 it is out of phase and cancels.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Ports 2 and 3 are in phase with each other, hence this is an example of a 0° hybrid.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Figure 12 shows a planar implementation but this design can also be implemented in coax or waveguide.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The hybrid ring is not symmetric on its ports; choosing a different port as the input does not necessarily produce the same results.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] With port 1 or port 3 as the input the hybrid ring is a 0° hybrid as stated.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] However using port 2 or port 4 as the input results in a 180° hybrid.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This fact leads to another useful application of the hybrid ring: it can be used to produce sum (Σ) and difference (Δ) signals from two input signals as shown in figure 12.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] With inputs to ports 2 and 3, the Σ signal appears at port 1 and the Δ signal appears at port 4.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A typical power divider is shown in figure 13.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Ideally, input power would be divided equally between the output ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Dividers are made up of multiple couplers and, like couplers, may be reversed and used as multiplexers.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The drawback is that for a four channel multiplexer, the output consists of only 1/4 the power from each, and is relatively inefficient.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The reason for this is that at each combiner half the input power goes to port 4 and is dissipated in the termination load.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] If the two inputs were coherent the phases could be so arranged that cancellation occurred at port 4 and then all the power would go to port 1.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] However, multiplexer inputs are usually from entirely independent sources and therefore not coherent.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Lossless multiplexing can only be done with filter networks.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The branch-line coupler described above can also be implemented in waveguide.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] One of the most common, and simplest, waveguide directional couplers is the Bethe-hole directional coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This consists of two parallel waveguides, one stacked on top of the other, with a hole between them.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Some of the power from one guide is launched through the hole into the other.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The Bethe-hole coupler is another example of a backward coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The concept of the Bethe-hole coupler can be extended by providing multiple holes.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The design of such couplers has parallels with the multiple section coupled transmission lines.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Using multiple holes allows the bandwidth to be extended by designing the sections as a Butterworth, Chebyshev, or some other filter class.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The hole size is chosen to give the desired coupling for each section of the filter.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Design criteria are to achieve a substantially flat coupling together with high directivity over the desired band.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The Riblet short-slot coupler is two waveguides side-by-side with the side-wall in common instead of the long side as in the Bethe-hole coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A slot is cut in the sidewall to allow coupling.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This design is frequently used to produce a 3 dB coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The Schwinger reversed-phase coupler is another design using parallel waveguides, this time the long side of one is common with the short side-wall of the other.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Two off-centre slots are cut between the waveguides spaced λ/4 apart.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This design has the advantage of a substantially flat directivity response and the disadvantage of a strongly frequency-dependent coupling compared to the Bethe-hole coupler, which has little variation in coupling factor.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The Moreno crossed-guide coupler has two waveguides stacked one on top of the other like the Bethe-hole coupler but at right angles to each other instead of parallel.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Two off-centre holes, usually cross-shaped are cut on the diagonal between the waveguides a distance $\scriptstyle {\sqrt {2}}\lambda /4$ apart.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The Moreno coupler is good for tight coupling applications.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] It is a compromise between the properties of the Bethe-hole and Schwinger couplers with both coupling and directivity varying with frequency.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The hybrid ring discussed above can also be implemented in waveguide.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Coherent power division was first accomplished by means of simple Tee junctions.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] At microwave frequencies, waveguide tees have two possible forms – the E-plane and H-plane.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] These two junctions split power equally, but because of the different field configurations at the junction, the electric fields at the output arms are in phase for the H-plane tee and are 180° out of phase for the E-plane tee.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The combination of these two tees to form a hybrid tee is known as the magic tee.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The magic tee is a four-port component which can perform the vector sum (Σ) and difference (Δ) of two coherent microwave signals.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The standard 3 dB hybrid transformer is shown in figure 16.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Power at port 1 is split equally between ports 2 and 3 but in antiphase to each other.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The hybrid transformer is therefore a 180° hybrid.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The centre-tap is usually terminated internally but it is possible to bring it out as port 4; in which case the hybrid can be used as a sum and difference hybrid.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] However, port 4 presents as a different impedance to the other ports and will require an additional transformer for impedance conversion if it is required to use this port at the same system impedance.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Hybrid transformers are commonly used in telecommunications for 2 to 4 wire conversion.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Telephone handsets include such a converter to convert the 2-wire line to the 4 wires from the earpiece and mouthpiece.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] For lower frequencies (less than 600 MHz) a compact broadband implementation by means of RF transformers is possible.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In figure 17 a circuit is shown which is meant for weak coupling and can be understood along these lines: A signal is coming in one line pair.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] One transformer reduces the voltage of the signal the other reduces the current.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The same argument holds for every other direction of a signal through the coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The relative sign of the induced voltage and current determines the direction of the outgoing signal.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] is the secondary to primary turns ratio.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] For a 3 dB coupling, that is equal splitting of the signal between the transmitted port and the coupled port, $\scriptstyle n={\sqrt {2}}$ and the isolated port is terminated in twice the characteristic impedance – 100 Ω for a 50 Ω system.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A 3 dB power divider based on this circuit has the two outputs in 180° phase to each other, compared to λ/4 coupled lines which have a 90° phase relationship.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A simple tee circuit of resistors can be used as a power divider as shown in figure 18.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This circuit can also be implemented as a delta circuit by applying the Y-Δ transform.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The delta form uses resistors that are equal to the system impedance.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This can be advantageous because precision resistors of the value of the system impedance are always available for most system nominal impedances.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The tee circuit has the benefits of simplicity, low cost, and intrinsically wide bandwidth.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] It has two major drawbacks; first, the circuit will dissipate power since it is resistive: an equal split will result in 6 dB insertion loss instead of 3 dB.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The second problem is that there is 0 dB directivity leading to very poor isolation between the output ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The insertion loss is not such a problem for an unequal split of power: for instance -40 dB at port 3 has an insertion loss less than 0.2 dB at port 2.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Isolation can be improved at the expense of insertion loss at both output ports by replacing the output resistors with T pads.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The isolation improvement is greater than the insertion loss added.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] A true hybrid divider/coupler with, theoretically, infinite isolation and directivity can be made from a resistive bridge circuit.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Like the tee circuit, the bridge has 6 dB insertion loss.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] It has the disadvantage that it cannot be used with unbalanced circuits without the addition of transformers; however, it is ideal for 600 Ω balanced telecommunication lines if the insertion loss is not an issue.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The resistors in the bridge which represent ports are not usually part of the device (with the exception of port 4 which may well be left permanently terminated internally) these being provided by the line terminations.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The device thus consists essentially of two resistors (plus the port 4 termination).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The above 6 dB coupler can be generalized to couplers with arbitrary coupling ratio.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Consider the following 5 resistor bridge circuit, where the resistor ratios $r=R_{5}/R_{2}=R_{3}/R_{6}$ of the 2 arms are equal.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In typical application, drive resistance $R_{1}=Z_{0}$ is the characteristic impedance, typically 50 $\Omega$ in radiowave and microwave circuits.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Port 2 and 3 are not internal to the hybrid, rather, they are connected to external loads, typically $R_{2}=R_{3}=Z_{0}$ .
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Under these conditions, the entire circuit has an input impedance of $Z_{0}$ , i.e. port 1 sees a matched load.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The coupling port (P3) voltage ratio is $r/(1+r)$ , the through port (P2) voltage ratio is $1/(1+r)$ .
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This circuit has a theoretical infinite reverse isolation when $R_{4}=Z_{0}$ .
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] To see this, connect port 2 to a floating source.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The bridge is balanced and there is no voltage across port 3, i.e. infinite reverse isolation.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] One disadvantage is of this hybrid is that only port 1 and 3 are ground referenced.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] When using single ended sources and loads, port 2 needs to be transformed from ground referenced to floating.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This can be done with a balun or specifically, a common-mode choke.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This can be further extended to a full 4 port hybrid coupler by connecting two hybrids back to back, sharing the same balun.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The coupled output from the directional coupler can be used to monitor frequency and power level on the signal without interrupting the main power flow in the system (except for a power reduction – see figure 3).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] If isolation is high, directional couplers are good for combining signals to feed a single line to a receiver for two-tone receiver tests.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In figure 20, one signal enters port P3 and one enters port P2, while both exit port P1.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The signal from port P3 to port P1 will experience 10 dB of loss, and the signal from port P2 to port P1 will have 0.5 dB loss.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The internal load on the isolated port will dissipate the signal losses from port P3 and port P2.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] If the isolators in figure 20 are neglected, the isolation measurement (port P2 to port P3) determines the amount of power from the signal generator F2 that will be injected into the signal generator F1.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] As the injection level increases, it may cause modulation of signal generator F1, or even injection phase locking.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Because of the symmetry of the directional coupler, the reverse injection will happen with the same possible modulation problems of signal generator F2 by F1.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Therefore, the isolators are used in figure 20 to effectively increase the isolation (or directivity) of the directional coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Consequently, the injection loss will be the isolation of the directional coupler plus the reverse isolation of the isolator.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Applications of the hybrid include monopulse comparators, mixers, power combiners, dividers, modulators, and phased array radar antenna systems.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Both in-phase devices (such as the Wilkinson divider) and quadrature (90°) hybrid couplers may be used for coherent power divider applications.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] An example of quadrature hybrids being used in a coherent power combiner application is given in the next section.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] An inexpensive version of the power divider, shown in figure 16, is used in the home to divide cable TV or over-the-air TV signals to multiple TV sets and other devices.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Multiport splitters with more than two output ports usually consist internally of a number of cascaded couplers.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Domestic broadband internet service can be provided by cable TV companies (cable internet).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The domestic user's internet cable modem is connected to one port of the splitter.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Since hybrid circuits are bi-directional, they can be used to coherently combine power as well as splitting it.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] In figure 21, an example is shown of a signal split up to feed multiple low power amplifiers, then recombined to feed a single antenna with high power.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The phases of the inputs to each power combiner are arranged such that the two inputs are 90° out of phase with each other.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Since the coupled port of a hybrid combiner is 90° out of phase with the transmitted port, this causes the powers to add at the output of the combiner and to cancel at the isolated port: a representative example from figure 21 is shown in figure 22.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Note that there is an additional fixed 90° phase shift to both ports at each combiner/divider which is not shown in the diagrams for simplicity.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Applying in-phase power to both input ports would not get the desired result: the quadrature sum of the two inputs would appear at both output ports – that is half the total power out of each.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This approach allows the use of numerous less expensive and lower-power amplifiers in the circuitry instead of a single high-power TWT.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Yet another approach is to have each solid state amplifier (SSA) feed an antenna and let the power be combined in space or be used to feed a lens attached to an antenna.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The phase properties of a 90° hybrid coupler can be used to great advantage in microwave circuits.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] For example, in a balanced microwave amplifier the two input stages are fed through a hybrid coupler.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The FET device normally has a very poor match and reflects much of the incident energy.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] However, since the devices are essentially identical the reflection coefficients from each device are equal.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] The reflected voltage from the FETs are in phase at the isolated port and are 180° different at the input port.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Therefore, all of the reflected power from the FETs goes to the load at the isolated port and no power goes to the input port.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] This results in a good input match (low VSWR).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] If phase-matched lines are used for an antenna input to a 180° hybrid coupler as shown in figure 23, a null will occur directly between the antennas.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] To receive a signal in that position, one would have to either change the hybrid type or line length.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] To reject a signal from a given direction, or create the difference pattern for a monopulse radar, this is a good approach.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] Phase-difference couplers can be used to create beam tilt in a VHF FM radio station, by delaying the phase to the lower elements of an antenna array.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/directional-coupler] More generally, phase-difference couplers, together with fixed phase delays and antenna arrays, are used in beam-forming networks such as the Butler matrix, to create a radio beam in any prescribed direction.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A **network analyzer** is an instrument that measures the network parameters of electrical networks.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Today, network analyzers commonly measure s–parameters because reflection and transmission of electrical networks are easy to measure at high frequencies, but there are other network parameter sets such as y-parameters, z-parameters, and h-parameters.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Network analyzers are often used to characterize two-port networks such as amplifiers and filters, but they can be used on networks with an arbitrary number of ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Network analyzers are used mostly at high frequencies; operating frequencies can range from 1 Hz to 1.5 THz.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Special types of network analyzers can also cover lower frequency ranges down to 1 Hz.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] These network analyzers can be used, for example, for the stability analysis of open loops or for the measurement of audio and ultrasonic components.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A VNA is a form of RF network analyzer widely used for RF design applications.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A VNA may also be called a **gain–phase meter** or an **automatic network analyzer**.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] An SNA is functionally identical to a spectrum analyzer in combination with a tracking generator.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] As of 2007, VNAs are the most common type of network analyzers, and so references to an unqualified "network analyzer" most often mean a VNA.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Seven prominent VNA manufacturers are Keysight, Anritsu, Advantest, Rohde & Schwarz, SIGLENT Technologies, Copper Mountain Technologies, and OMICRON Lab.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] For some years now, entry-level devices and do-it-yourself projects have also been available, some for less than $100, mainly from the amateur radio sector.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Although these have significantly reduced features compared to professional devices and offer only a limited range of functions, they are often sufficient for private users - especially during studies and for hobby applications up to the single-digit GHz range.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Another category of network analyzer is the **microwave transition analyzer** (MTA) or **large-signal network analyzer** (LSNA), which measure both amplitude and phase of the fundamental and harmonics.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The MTA was commercialized before the LSNA, but was lacking some of the user-friendly calibration features now available with the LSNA.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The basic architecture of a network analyzer involves a signal generator, a test set, one or more receivers and display.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] In some setups, these units are distinct instruments.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Most VNAs have two test ports, permitting measurement of four S-parameters $(S_{11},S_{21},S_{12},S_{22})$ , but instruments with more than two ports are available commercially.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The network analyzer needs a test signal, and a signal generator or signal source will provide one.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Older network analyzers did not have their own signal generator, but had the ability to control a stand-alone signal generator using, for example, a GPIB connection.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Nearly all modern network analyzers have a built-in signal generator.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] High-performance network analyzers have two built-in sources.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Two built-in sources are useful for applications such as mixer test, where one source provides the RF signal, another the LO; or amplifier intermodulation testing, where two tones are required for the test.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The test set takes the signal generator output and routes it to the device under test, and it routes the signal to be measured to the receivers.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] It often splits off a reference channel for the incident wave.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] In a SNA, the reference channel may go to a diode detector (receiver) whose output is sent to the signal generator's automatic level control.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The result is better control of the signal generator's output and better measurement accuracy.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] In a VNA, the reference channel goes to the receivers; it is needed to serve as a phase reference.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Directional couplers or two resistor power dividers are used for signal separation.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Some microwave test sets include the front end mixers for the receivers (e.g., test sets for HP 8510).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A network analyzer will have one or more receivers connected to its test ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The reference test port is usually labeled **R**, and the primary test ports are **A**, **B**, **C**, ...
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Some analyzers will dedicate a separate receiver to each test port, but others share one or two receivers among the ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The **R** receiver may be less sensitive than the receivers used on the test ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] For the SNA, the receiver only measures the magnitude of the signal.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A receiver can be a detector diode that operates at the test frequency.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The simplest SNA will have a single test port, but more accurate measurements are made when a reference port is also used.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The reference port will compensate for amplitude variations in the test signal at the measurement plane.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] It is possible to share a single detector and use it for both the reference port and the test port by making two measurement passes.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] For the VNA, the receiver measures both the magnitude and the phase of the signal.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] It needs a reference channel (**R**) to determine the phase, so a VNA needs at least two receivers.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The usual method down converts the reference and test channels to make the measurements at a lower frequency.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The phase may be measured with a quadrature detector.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A VNA requires at least two receivers, but some will have three or four receivers to permit simultaneous measurement of different parameters.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] There are some VNA architectures (six-port reflectometer) that infer phase and magnitude from just power measurements.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] With the processed RF signal available from the receiver / detector section it is necessary to display the signal in a format that can be interpreted.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] With the levels of processing that are available today, some very sophisticated solutions are available in RF network analyzers.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Here the reflection and transmission data is formatted to enable the information to be interpreted as easily as possible.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Most RF network analyzers incorporate features including linear and logarithmic sweeps, linear and log formats, polar plots, Smith charts, etc.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Trace markers, limit lines and pass/fail criteria are also added in many instances.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A VNA is a test system that enables the RF performance of radio frequency and microwave devices to be characterised in terms of network scattering parameters, or S parameters.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The diagram shows the essential parts of a typical 2-port vector network analyzer (VNA).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The two ports of the device under test (DUT) are denoted port 1 (P1) and port 2 (P2).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The test port connectors provided on the VNA itself are precision types which will normally have to be extended and connected to P1 and P2 using precision cables 1 and 2, PC1 and PC2 respectively and suitable connector adaptors A1 and A2 respectively.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The test frequency is generated by a variable frequency CW source and its power level is set using a variable attenuator.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The position of switch SW1 sets the direction that the test signal passes through the DUT.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Initially consider that SW1 is at position 1 so that the test signal is incident on the DUT at P1 which is appropriate for measuring $S_{11}\,$ and $S_{21}\,$ .
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The test signal is fed by SW1 to the common port of splitter 1, one arm (the reference channel) feeding a reference receiver for P1 (RX REF1) and the other (the test channel) connecting to P1 via the directional coupler DC1, PC1 and A1.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The third port of DC1 couples off the power reflected from P1 via A1 and PC1, then feeding it to test receiver 1 (RX TEST1).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Similarly, signals leaving P2 pass via A2, PC2 and DC2 to RX TEST2.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] RX REF1, RX TEST1, RX REF2 and RXTEST2 are known as coherent receivers as they share the same reference oscillator, and they are capable of measuring the test signal's amplitude *and* phase at the test frequency.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] All of the complex receiver output signals are fed to a processor which does the mathematical processing and displays the chosen parameters and format on the phase and amplitude display.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The instantaneous value of phase includes both the temporal and spatial parts, but the former is removed by virtue of using 2 test channels, one as a reference and the other for measurement.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] When SW1 is set to position 2, the test signals are applied to P2, the reference is measured by RX REF2, reflections from P2 are coupled off by DC2 and measured by RX TEST2 and signals leaving P1 are coupled off by DC1 and measured by RX TEST1.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] This position is appropriate for measuring $S_{22}\,$ and $S_{12}\,$ .
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A network analyzer, like most electronic instruments requires periodic calibration; typically this is performed once per year and is performed by the manufacturer or by a 3rd party in a calibration laboratory.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] When the instrument is calibrated, a sticker will usually be attached, stating the date it was calibrated and when the next calibration is due.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A calibration certificate will be issued.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A vector network analyzer achieves highly accurate measurements by correcting for the systematic errors in the instrument, the characteristics of cables, adapters and test fixtures.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The process of error correction, although commonly just called calibration, is an entirely different process, and may be performed by an engineer several times in an hour.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Sometimes it is called user-calibration, to indicate the difference from periodic calibration by a manufacturer.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A network analyzer has connectors on its front panel, but the measurements are seldom made at the front panel.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Usually some test cables will connect from the front panel to the device under test (DUT).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The length of those cables will introduce a time delay and corresponding phase shift (affecting VNA measurements); the cables will also introduce some attenuation (affecting SNA and VNA measurements).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The same is true for cables and couplers inside the network analyzer.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] All these factors will change with temperature.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Calibration usually involves measuring known standards and using those measurements to compensate for systematic errors, but there are methods which do not require known standards.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Only systematic errors can be corrected.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Random errors, such as connector repeatability cannot be corrected by the user calibration.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] However, some portable vector network analyzers, designed for lower accuracy measurement outside using batteries, do attempt some correction for temperature by measuring the internal temperature of the network analyzer.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] There are several different methods of calibration.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The simplest calibration that can be performed on a network analyzer is a transmission measurement.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] This gives no phase information, and so gives similar data to a scalar network analyzer.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The simplest calibration that can be performed on a network analyzer, whilst providing phase information is a 1-port calibration (S11 or S22, but not both).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] In a typical 1-port reflection calibration, the user measures three known standards, usually an open, a short and a known load.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] From these three measurements the network analyzer can account for the three errors above.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A more complex calibration is a full 2-port reflectivity and transmission calibration.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] For two ports there are 12 possible systematic errors analogous to the three above.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The most common method for correcting for these involves measuring a short, load and open standard on each of the two ports, as well as transmission between the two ports.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] It is impossible to make a perfect short circuit, as there will always be some inductance in the short.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] It is impossible to make a perfect open circuit, as there will always be some fringing capacitance.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A modern network analyzer will have data stored about the devices in a calibration kit.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] (Keysight Technologies 2006) harv error: no target: CITEREFKeysight_Technologies2006 (help) For the open-circuit, this will be some electrical delay (typically tens of picoseconds), and fringing capacitance which will be frequency dependent.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The capacitance is normally specified in terms of a polynomial, with the coefficients specific to each standard.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A short will have some delay, and a frequency dependent inductance, although the inductance is normally considered insignificant below about 6 GHz.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The definitions for a number of standards used in Keysight calibration kits can be found at http://na.support.keysight.com/pna/caldefs/stddefs.html The definitions of the standards for a particular calibration kit will often change depending on the frequency range of the network analyzer.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] If a calibration kit works to 9 GHz, but a particular network analyzer has a maximum frequency of operation of 3 GHz, then the capacitance of the open standard can approximated more closely up to 3 GHz, using a different set of coefficients than are necessary to work up to 9 GHz.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] In some calibration kits, the data on the males is different from the females, so the user needs to specify the gender of the connector.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Keysight 85033E 9 GHz 3.5 mm), the male and female have identical characteristics, so there is no need for the user to specify the gender.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] For gender-less connectors, like APC-7, this issue does not arise.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Most network analyzers have the ability to have a user defined calibration kit.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] So if a user has a particular calibration kit details of which are not in the firmware of the network analyzer, the data about the kit can be loaded into the network analyzer and so the kit used.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Typically the calibration data can be entered on the instrument front panel or loaded from a medium such as floppy disk or USB stick, or down a bus such as USB or GPIB.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The more expensive calibration kits will usually include a torque wrench to tighten connectors properly and a connector gauge to ensure there are no gross errors in the connectors.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] A calibration using a mechanical calibration kit may take a significant amount of time.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Not only must the operator sweep through all the frequencies of interest, but the operator must also disconnect and reconnect the various standards.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] 9) To avoid that work, network analyzers can employ automated calibration standards.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] (Keysight Technologies 2003) The operator connects one box to the network analyzer.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The box has a set of standards inside and some switches that have already been characterized.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The network analyzer can read the characterization and control the configuration using a digital bus such as USB.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Many verification kits are available to verify the network analyzer is performing to specification.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] These typically consist of transmission lines with an air dielectric and attenuators.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The Keysight 85055A verification kit includes a 10 cm airline, stepped impedance airline, 20 dB and 50 dB attenuators with data on the devices measured by the manufacturer and stored on both a floppy disk and USB flash drive.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Older versions of the 85055A have the data stored on tape and floppy disks rather than on USB drives.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] Verification kits are also manufactured for other transmission lines such as waveguide which contain a known through mismatch and attenuations.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The Flann verification kit includes 5 mismatches using a decrease in waveguide height to provide a known VSWR and 2 attenuators of differing attenuation levels.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The three major manufacturers of VNAs, Keysight, Anritsu, and Rohde & Schwarz, all produce models which extend the functionality of their products to also include measurement of noise figure.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/network-analyzer-electrical] The vector error correction permits higher accuracy than is possible with other forms of commercial noise figure meters.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] A **time-domain reflectometer** (**TDR**) is an electronic instrument used to determine the characteristics of electrical lines by observing reflected pulses.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] It can be used to characterize and locate faults in metallic cables (for example, twisted pair wire or coaxial cable), and to locate discontinuities in a connector, printed circuit board, or any other electrical path.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] A TDR measures reflections along a conductor.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] In order to measure those reflections, the TDR will transmit an incident signal onto the conductor and listen for its reflections.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] If the conductor is of a uniform impedance and is properly terminated, then there will be no reflections and the remaining incident signal will be absorbed at the far-end by the termination.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Instead, if there are impedance variations, then some of the incident signal will be reflected back to the source.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The impedance of the discontinuity can be determined from the amplitude of the reflected signal.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The distance to the reflecting impedance can also be determined from the time that a pulse takes to return.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The limitation of this method is the minimum system rise time.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The total rise time consists of the combined rise time of the driving pulse and that of the oscilloscope or sampler that monitors the reflections.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The TDR analysis begins with the propagation of a step or impulse of energy into a system and the subsequent observation of the energy reflected by the system.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] By analyzing the magnitude, duration and shape of the reflected waveform, the nature of the impedance variation in the transmission system can be determined.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] If a pure resistive load is placed on the output of the reflectometer and a step signal is applied, a step signal is observed on the display, and its height is a function of the resistance.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] where $Z_{0}$ is the characteristic impedance of the transmission line.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Generally, the reflections will have the same shape as the incident signal, but their sign and magnitude depend on the change in impedance level.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] If there is a step increase in the impedance, then the reflection will have the same sign as the incident signal; if there is a step decrease in impedance, the reflection will have the opposite sign.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The magnitude of the reflection depends not only on the amount of the impedance change, but also upon the loss in the conductor.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The reflections are measured at the output/input to the TDR and displayed or plotted as a function of time.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Alternatively, the display can be read as a function of cable length because the speed of signal propagation is almost constant for a given transmission medium.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Because of its sensitivity to impedance variations, a TDR may be used to verify cable impedance characteristics, splice and connector locations and associated losses, and estimate cable lengths.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Some TDRs transmit a pulse along the conductor; the resolution of such instruments is often the width of the pulse.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Narrow pulses can offer good resolution, but they have high frequency signal components that are attenuated in long cables.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The shape of the pulse is often a half cycle sinusoid.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] For longer cables, wider pulse widths are used.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Instead of looking for the reflection of a complete pulse, the instrument is concerned with the rising edge, which can be very fast.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] A 1970s technology TDR used steps with a rise time of 25 ps.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Still other TDRs transmit complex signals and detect reflections with correlation techniques.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] See spread-spectrum time-domain reflectometry.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The equivalent device for optical fiber is an optical time-domain reflectometer.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] For example, spread-spectrum time-domain reflectometry (SSTDR) is used to detect intermittent faults in complex and high-noise systems such as aircraft wiring.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Coherent optical time domain reflectometry (COTDR) is another variant, used in optical systems, in which the returned signal is mixed with a local oscillator and then filtered to reduce noise.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] These traces were produced by a time-domain reflectometer made from common lab equipment connected to approximately 100 feet (30 m) of coaxial cable having a characteristic impedance of 50 ohms.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The propagation velocity of this cable is approximately 66% of the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] These traces were produced by a commercial TDR using a step waveform with a 25 ps risetime, a sampling head with a 35 ps risetime, and an 18-inch (0.46 m) SMA cable.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The far end of the SMA cable was left open or connected to different adapters.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] It takes about 3 ns for the pulse to travel down the cable, reflect, and reach the sampling head.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] A second reflection (at about 6 ns) can be seen in some traces; it is due to the reflection seeing a small mismatch at the sampling head and causing another "incident" wave to travel down the cable.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] If the far end of the cable is shorted, that is, terminated with an impedance of zero ohms, and when the rising edge of the pulse is launched down the cable, the voltage at the launching point "steps up" to a given value instantly and the pulse begins propagating in the cable towards the short.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] When the pulse encounters the short, no energy is absorbed at the far end.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Instead, an inverted pulse reflects back from the short towards the launching end.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] It is only when this reflection finally reaches the launch point that the voltage at this point abruptly drops back to zero, signaling the presence of a short at the end of the cable.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] That is, the TDR has no indication that there is a short at the end of the cable until its emitted pulse can travel in the cable and the echo can return.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] It is only after this round-trip delay that the short can be detected by the TDR.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] With knowledge of the signal propagation speed in the particular cable-under-test, the distance to the short can be measured.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] A similar effect occurs if the far end of the cable is an open circuit (terminated into an infinite impedance).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] In this case, though, the reflection from the far end is polarized identically with the original pulse and adds to it rather than cancelling it out.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] So after a round-trip delay, the voltage at the TDR abruptly jumps to twice the originally-applied voltage.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Perfect termination at the far end of the cable would entirely absorb the applied pulse without causing any reflection, rendering the determination of the actual length of the cable impossible.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] In practice, some small reflection is nearly always observed.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The magnitude of the reflection is referred to as the reflection coefficient or *ρ*.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The coefficient ranges from 1 (open circuit) to −1 (short circuit).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The value of zero means that there is no reflection.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The reflection coefficient is calculated as follows: $\rho ={\frac {Z_{\text{t}}-Z_{\text{o}}}{Z_{\text{t}}+Z_{\text{o}}}}$ where *Z*o is defined as the characteristic impedance of the transmission medium and *Z*t is the impedance of the termination at the far end of the transmission line.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Any discontinuity can be viewed as a termination impedance and substituted as *Z*t.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] This includes abrupt changes in the characteristic impedance.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] As an example, a trace width on a printed circuit board doubled at its midsection would constitute a discontinuity.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Some of the energy will be reflected back to the driving source; the remaining energy will be transmitted.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] This is also known as a scattering junction.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Time domain reflectometers are commonly used for in-place testing of very long cable runs, where it is impractical to dig up or remove what may be a kilometers-long cable.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] They are indispensable for preventive maintenance of telecommunication lines, as TDRs can detect resistance on joints and connectors as they corrode, and increasing insulation leakage as it degrades and absorbs moisture, long before either leads to catastrophic failures.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Using a TDR, it is possible to pinpoint a fault to within centimetres.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] TDRs are also very useful tools for technical surveillance counter-measures, where they help determine the existence and location of wire taps.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The slight change in line impedance caused by the introduction of a tap or splice will show up on the screen of a TDR when connected to a phone line.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] TDR equipment is also an essential tool in the failure analysis of modern high-frequency printed circuit boards with signal traces crafted to emulate transmission lines.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Observing reflections can detect any unsoldered pins of a ball grid array device.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Short-circuited pins can also be detected similarly.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The TDR principle is used in industrial settings, in situations as diverse as the testing of integrated circuit packages to measuring liquid levels.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] In the former, the time domain reflectometer is used to isolate failing sites in the same.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The latter is primarily limited to the process industry.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] In a TDR-based level measurement device, the device generates an impulse that propagates down a thin waveguide (referred to as a probe) – typically a metal rod or a steel cable.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] When this impulse hits the surface of the medium to be measured, part of the impulse reflects back up the waveguide.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The device determines the fluid level by measuring the time difference between when the impulse was sent and when the reflection returned.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The sensors can output the analyzed level as a continuous analog signal or switch output signals.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] In TDR technology, the impulse velocity is primarily affected by the permittivity of the medium through which the pulse propagates, which can vary greatly by the moisture content and temperature of the medium.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] In many cases, this effect can be corrected without undue difficulty.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] In some cases, such as in boiling and/or high temperature environments, the correction can be difficult.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] In particular, determining the froth (foam) height and the collapsed liquid level in a frothy / boiling medium can be very difficult.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The Dam Safety Interest Group of CEA Technologies, Inc.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] (CEATI), a consortium of electrical power organizations, has applied Spread-spectrum time-domain reflectometry to identify potential faults in concrete dam anchor cables.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The key benefit of Time Domain reflectometry over other testing methods is the non-destructive method of these tests.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] A TDR is used to determine moisture content in soil and porous media.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Over the last two decades, substantial advances have been made measuring moisture in soil, grain, food stuff, and sediment.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Recent reviews and reference work on the subject include, Topp and Reynolds (1998), Noborio (2001), Pettinellia et al.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The TDR method is a transmission line technique, and determines apparent permittivity (Ka) from the travel time of an electromagnetic wave that propagates along a transmission line, usually two or more parallel metal rods embedded in soil or sediment.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The probes are typically between 10 and 30 cm long and connected to the TDR via coaxial cable.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Time domain reflectometry has also been utilized to monitor slope movement in a variety of geotechnical settings, including highway cuts, rail beds, and open pit mines (Dowding & O'Connor, 1984, 2000a, 2000b; Kane & Beck, 1999).
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] In TDR stability monitoring applications, a coaxial cable is installed in a vertical borehole passing through the region of concern.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The electrical impedance at any point along a coaxial cable changes with deformation of the insulator between the conductors.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] A brittle grout surrounds the cable to translate earth movement into an abrupt cable deformation that shows up as a detectable peak in the reflectance trace.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Until recently, the technique was relatively insensitive to small slope movements and could not be automated because it relied on human detection of changes in the reflectance trace over time.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Farrington and Sargand (2004) developed a simple signal processing technique using numerical derivatives to extract reliable indications of slope movement from the TDR data much earlier than by conventional interpretation.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Another application of TDRs in geotechnical engineering is to determine the soil moisture content.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] This can be done by placing the TDRs in different soil layers and measuring the time of start of precipitation and the time that TDR indicates an increase in the soil moisture content.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The depth of the TDR (d) is a known factor and the other is the time it takes the drop of water to reach that depth (*t*); therefore the speed of water infiltration (*v*) can be determined.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] This is a good method to assess the effectiveness of Best Management Practices (BMPs) in reducing stormwater surface runoff.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Time domain reflectometry is used in semiconductor failure analysis as a non-destructive method for the location of defects in semiconductor device packages.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] The TDR provides an electrical signature of individual conductive traces in the device package, and is useful for determining the location of opens and shorts.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Time domain reflectometry, specifically spread-spectrum time-domain reflectometry is used on aviation wiring for both preventive maintenance and fault location.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Spread spectrum time domain reflectometry has the advantage of precisely locating the fault location within thousands of miles of aviation wiring.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Additionally, this technology is worth considering for real time aviation monitoring, as spread spectrum reflectometry can be employed on live wires.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] This method has been shown to be useful to locating intermittent electrical faults.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Multi carrier time domain reflectometry (MCTDR) has also been identified as a promising method for embedded EWIS diagnosis or troubleshooting tools.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Based on the injection of a multicarrier signal (respecting EMC and harmless for the wires), this smart technology provides information for the detection, localization and characterization of electrical defects (or mechanical defects having electrical consequences) in the wiring systems.
[src:vector-network-analyzer/time-domain-reflectometer] Hard fault (short, open circuit) or intermittent defects can be detected very quickly increasing the reliability of wiring systems and improving their maintenance.
